methodology: Algorithmic mapping from v2 scores (35-62) to 5-axis ratings using sector phase, force velocity, and architecture type as modifiers. These 287 models lack individual IDs — only 7 notable low-ranked models have IDs. The rest are characterized by distribution only.

mapping_rules.base_composite: v2_score × 0.95 (slight penalty for lower-ranked models lacking deep validation)

by_architecture_estimated.v3_context: Physical assets + Silver Tsunami timing + SBA 504 = highest upward mobility in this batch. Best acquire_and_modernize models could reach TIMING_ARBITRAGE with updated sector data.
Revenue-generating from day 1, but competitive. Fear friction matters — FSR models in high-fear sectors (healthcare, legal) get psychology penalty.
Platform plays at this score range face crowded competition and capital requirements. Perez crash vulnerability is high. Most should be PARKED.
The 7 notable low-ranked models are ALL vertical SaaS — facing funded incumbents (Gusto $746M, Abridge $250M, Tractable $115M). This architecture is the most crowded.
Network effects are valuable but require capital. At this score range, the network effects are weak or the market is too small.
EU AI Act creates new regulatory moats. Models serving compliance needs get +2 from F3 acceleration. Some could upgrade to FEAR_ECONOMY category.
Data moats build over time but require capital runway. At this score range, the data advantage isn't strong enough or the market is too small.
Physical production + AI = high crash resilience. Capital rotation from digital to physical (ETF data: Industrials +15.1%, Materials +20.1%) validates these. Some could reach CAPITAL_MOAT.
Rollup models benefit from PE refinancing wall (distressed targets) and Silver Tsunami. Those targeting manufacturing/trades get timing boost.
Time-sensitive models. Those targeting the PE refinancing wall ($936B-$1.8T maturing 2026-2028) get timing upgrade. Others may have missed their window.
